rectal examination reveals a firm, irregular prostate with nodules palpable in both lobes but confined to the prostate gland.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following correctly describes the TNM staging of prostate cancer?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["T4 - extracapsular extension","T0 - clinically inapparent tumour","M1a - metastasis in regional lymph nodes","T2c - tumour involves both lobes","T3a - invades bladder sphincter"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ETNM staging is crucial for determining prognosis and treatment in prostate cancer. Understanding the correct staging definitions is essential for appropriate management.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ET2c\u003C/strong\u003E correctly describes a tumour that involves both lobes of the prostate but remains confined within the prostate capsule. This matches the clinical findings in the stem where nodules are palpable in both lobes.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ET4\u003C/strong\u003E actually describes tumour invasion into adjacent structures (such as external sphincter, rectum, levator muscles, or pelvic wall). Extracapsular extension is classified as T3a.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ET0\u003C/strong\u003E indicates no evidence of primary tumour, while clinically inapparent tumour found by needle biopsy is classified as T1c.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EM1a\u003C/strong\u003E describes metastasis to non-regional lymph nodes. Regional lymph node involvement is classified under N staging.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ET3a\u003C/strong\u003E describes extracapsular extension (unilateral or bilateral), not invasion of the bladder sphincter which would be T4.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe TNM staging system for prostate cancer is regularly updated by the American Joint Committee on Cancer (AJCC). The T stage describes the extent of the primary tumour, N stage describes regional lymph node involvement, and M stage describes distant metastasis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["T staging in prostate cancer reflects the extent of local tumour spread, with T2c indicating bilateral disease confined within the prostate.","T3a indicates extracapsular extension, while T4 indicates invasion of adjacent structures.","M staging in prostate cancer uses M1a for non-regional lymph node metastases."],"references":["Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Cheng L, Montironi R, Bostwick DG, Lopez-Beltran A, Berney DM. Staging of prostate cancer. Histopathology. 2012 Jan;60(1):87-117. doi: 10.1111/j.1365-2559.2011.04025.x. PMID: 22212080.","Pospihalj B. Staging of prostate cancer: a review with reference for further refinement. Anal Quant Cytopathol Histpathol. 2015 Feb;37(1):69-74. PMID: 26072637."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45723"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15147"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45723","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/45723"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-10T19:49:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-10T19:50:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7835"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60301"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attribute